Mobiles.LongDescription: `aThe giant ant scans the tree with his feelers.``
Mobiles.Description: The ant looks to be from a messed experiment of an alchemist.  It'sfeelers are mutated and appear to me much longer then an ants of that sizeshould be.  Although, it looks to be peaceful, a fight with it would bedeadly.

Mobiles.LongDescription: `hA`d foul-looking`h guard growls as he fights off yet another Continuum knight.``
Mobiles.Description: This foul-looking guard is huge and powerful, so you decide not to tellhim about his appearence.  In fact, if he asks, you'll tell him you love thecombination of bird and man, and are jealous of his primarily bird physique.If he fights as well as he is ugly, you will surely die.

Mobiles.LongDescription: `dA Keep Guard is fighting off the intruders!``
Mobiles.Description: This guard is of a different breed then the other guards outside theKeep.  He appears to be much stronger and much better equipped.  His musclesbulge out past his montrous wings as they ruffle in the wind.

Mobiles.LongDescription: `dA Krathen Flag Guard leads a group of soldiers here.``
Mobiles.Description: The monstrous guard looks so much more deadly then the other guards.  Helooks to be twice the size of the other guards, along with twice as strongand quick.  He holds his chin high, as his muscles tense when you look athim, almost ready to strike.

Mobiles.LongDescription: `dA Tower Guard, sworn to defend the Krathen until death, bars your way.``
Mobiles.Description: The Tower Guard does not seem to be as big or husky as the other guardsof the Keep.  He is rather tall and lanky, and his wings are much longerthan usual, displaying that he is a strong flyer.  Also, all he is wearingis a pair of glasses, that seem to glow around his head.

Mobiles.LongDescription: `dA trainee of the Krathen army has been forced to defend his keep.``
Mobiles.Description: This trainee seems ready to bloom into an Elite Guard.  Small, but by theshape of his bones, he looks like he will be huge when he matures.

Mobiles.LongDescription: `dKrathe, the traitor of humans, leads his army to defend his keep!``
Mobiles.Description: Krathe, is huge, especially for a human.  His large size is verydeceiving of his battle quickness and prowess.  It is said he once foughtoff a whole army of men as he escaped to hide among the Krathen.  Variouscuts about his body show that it is true.

Mobiles.LongDescription: ``The `gGeneral`` of the Krathens stands here, musing over some battle plans.
Mobiles.Description: The General of the Krathe is a big, imposing Krathen.  He has, however, aslightly harried look at all times.  You wonder if it has anything to dowith the wedding ring he wears on a finger.

Mobiles.LongDescription: `dA Krathen woman runs around in panic.``
Mobiles.Description: `kShe is nude! Woohoo! Nothing beats nude women panicking!``

Mobiles.LongDescription: A krathen child tries to sneak by unnoticed.
`dThe alchemist huddles over some sickly, glowing potions, preparing healing potions for his comrades.``
`dAn old retired Krathen officer has once again picked up his sword.``
`dThe cook dodges swords and arrows, trying to escape the raging battle.``
Mobiles.Description: Grease splatters decorate the charred and stained apron worn by thisKrathe cook.  He holds a large, bloody cleaver in one hand with the kind ofcomfortable grip that suggests he doesn't like criticism of his food.

Mobiles.LongDescription: `dA woman kneels here at Krathe's feet, defending her master.``
`aAn ant twists and turns, following its own mysterious path.``
`eA `klightning bug `eflutters around.``
`oA huge `klightning bug`o hovers too close to your eyes.``
`cThe General's wife sits here, polishing some old armor.``
Mobiles.Description: This tall, birdlike woman sings tunefully under her breath as shepolishes an old piece of armor.  Looking closely at the armor she holds, youwonder who it is meant for, as surely it would never fit the massiveGeneral.  It definitely looks as if it were made for a more slender figure.As she turns the armor in her hands to better polish it, you catch a glimpseof the breastplate and realize...  That armor is for a woman.  Perhaps eventhe General's wife herself.  She doesn't seem so wimpy anymore, and youthink it might be a bad idea to ask her about her sewing or if she's donethe dishes lately.

Mobiles.LongDescription: `dA Keep Guard fends off intruders here.``
Mobiles.Description: This guard is of a different breed then the other guards outside theKeep.  He appears to be much stronger and much better equipped.  His musclesbulge out past his montrous wings as they ruffle in the wind.

Mobiles.LongDescription: `dA mechanical flailer awaits your trigger.``
`dAn orc butcher hides behind a corpse here.``
Mobiles.Description: An orc glowers at you with eyes too dead to feel anything but hate.  Hehas been a slave to the Krathe so long that he no longer remembers anythingbut his life here, and his hatred of his masters.  Because of the time he'sspent here, he has been given the position of butcher to the Cook.  As youwatch, he scratches idly at himself, dried gore flaking off to fall to thefloor.  How disgusting!

Mobiles.LongDescription: `oA giant of a man stands here, blocking your way with his shield.``
Mobiles.Description: `hThe siege knight stands here, blocking all access to the krathen keep.His work is to prevent people from walking into the `hraging battle.  Not aparticipant of the battle, his shining steel armor gleams like a mirror andhis heavy round-shield `hpresents a mighty obstacle on his arm.  With adetermined but friendly smile he denies you entrance to the keep.  ``

Mobiles.LongDescription: `oA knight of the Continuum order is fighting the Krathen army.``
`oA battle-cleric of the Continuum order throws holy fire at her enemies.``
Mobiles.Description: `hAs rays of holy light shoot out of her hands, this `hcleric ripsthrough her enemies.  Her robes are in disarray, but still untainted byblood.  `hA white leather book is tucked in her belt marked with thetell-tale sign `hof the Continuum order.  A`o radiant white aura`h surroundsher, and every weapon that passes `hthrough slows down, as if stuck in timeitself, making it easy for the cleric to dodge it.  ``

Mobiles.LongDescription: `oDodging the enemy's lunges and swings easily, a Continuum monk cuts through skin with rapid strikes.``
Mobiles.Description: `hClad in a loose cotton garb, this monk moves swiftly between theenemies, derilvering deadly `hstrikes with his hands and feet.  The samefanatism radiates from his sweaty face as the other `hinvaders of krathen.``

Rooms.RoomDescription: You stand before the trunk of a huge tree, that seems to reach into theheavens.  Although it seems to be very ancient, your kick to the trunkproves it to be very sturdy.  Some large, deep cut marks on the trunk drawyour attention and you think that you might be able to use the marks to beable to shimmy up the tree, although your stomach churns at the thought.
You hug the ancient tree for dear life as you shimmy up.  You noticerather peculiar looking ants chewing away at its bark, and hope that bark isthe only thing they like to chew on.

As you get higher and higher ascending the tree, its bark seems to getmore and more comfortable next to your body.  Its age seems to dissipate,and starts to resemble the strong bark of sapling in its prime.
With the bark starting to get more comfortable, it's also becoming muchmore easier to shimmy up.  You glance up and almost seem to make out themakings of some kind of town up in the trees.

From here you have the vantage of being above all other trees in theforest, which now seem to be nothing larger than petty shrubs waiting to bepruned.  You glance up and see a wooden platform that you can stand on andrest.

Rooms.RoomName: Entrance to the Keep of the Krathen
Rooms.RoomDescription: What previously appeared to be a resting area is actually the entrance toan intricately designed wooden keep; it could almost be called a giant treehouse.  Wiry bridges connect different huts and cabins on an intricatenetwork of branches.  To the north is a wiry bridge that leans across towhat seems to be the center of the keep.

Like the tree, this Bridge seems also to be very old, but alsodependable.  Only an inch thick, the rope still can bear an incredibleamount of weight.  You are thankful for this, knowing your life could easilyend if it snapped.

You stand firmly in the center of the tree, with small, seeminglyharmless huts branching out to your east and west.  To the north you see animposing fortress.  Before you stands some kind of a contraption that actsas a well which brings up buckets of water, slowly, from the now distantground.

Great rocks have totally obliterated the row of commons, wood and leavesmix with the bludgeoned remains of the krathen commoners and a few wingedsoldiers.  The surrounding greenery of the krathen tree is blackened by sootand blood, testament to the ongoing battle.  ``
Although this bridge is built with the same strong rope as the others, itis much more intricate in design.  It is knotted and tied in a way thatalmost looks fashionable.

The huts on this side of the Tree appear much larger and more richly madethan the common huts.  One of these buildings seems to larger than severalof the common huts, and the wood that composes each of these gives off asweet smell.

You stand before what appears to be the Church of the Krathen.  On top ofthis small abode, you see a statue that rises into the sky.  While youcannot yet make out the details of this statue, it seems to be a honorariumof their god.

An aura seems to envelop you as you enter this holy church.  Itsstructure is built in a way that you are not familiar with.  Huge beams ofsweet-smelling wood rise up and form the church in an undescribable way.Before you stands the statue of their god, Krathe.  Oddly, Krathe appears tobe human, looking nothing like the bird-like Krathens.

Debris covers the floor, the stairs and all exits except the entrance.  Ashort-lived battle seems to have taken place in here, gutted and mutilatedservants are piled near the door, as if defending the master of this mansionwith their lives.  Charred, ripped-out of pages of books lie near fires madeof torn-down tapestries.

To the North you see a mansion, that makes Governor Shik's hut look likea anthill.  It is made of thick planks of finely worked wood, seamed closetogether.  The windows are narrow and resemble arrow slits more than placesto look out of.  In fact, the whole thing, while elegantly made, looks morelike a fortress than a home.

Unlike the other homes, the General's Mansion actually looks more like ahouse than a hut.  The wood that composes it is much stronger and thicker,and overall the building looks sturdier than any of the others.  It almostseems as if the General wanted his own fort.

This room is the room where guests wait for the appearance of theGeneral.  Many pictures of the General and his descendants cover the wall.The singular lack and poor quality of light in this room forces you tostrain to see them.

You walk along a creaky old hallway which has been decorated withnumerous prizes of war garnered by the General, back in an olden age whenthe Krathen were once threats to civilization.  Old wooden doors provideviable exits to the north and south.

You are dumbfounded by the colourful works you see adorning the walls ofthis room.  They are unlike anything anyone has ever seen.  Some of thepaintings resemble the shapes on the hut doors, but you are perplexed by howanyone could consider this 'art' .

In this room, huge war trophies pour off the shelves that line the walls.Although you cannot understand the odd markings on or around each one, thesize and design of each trophy makes it clear these are great prizes.

This is obviously the room the General lives for, and in.  Ever since hisdefeat, he has spent years planning his revenge.  Covered in strategicallyplaced figurines resembling Krathen, Elves, Humans, and so on, a broad, longtable takes up most of the space.  From the pervasive odor and theoccasional heap of soiled clothing on the ground, the General must spend toomuch time here, and not enough engaged in hygenic activities.

Rooms.EnterMsg: The bridge sways gently as $n steps on.
Rooms.ExitMsg: The planks groan softly as $n walks away to the $T.
Rooms.RoomDescription: Unlike the other bridges, this one is made up of a much thicker, evenstronger rope covered with thick floorboards, specifically made for a largearmy.  Moments after each step, a gentle swaying rocks the bridge.  Aboveand around wind rustles in the leaves.  Sky is visible in shifting patchesabove.  In the keep, there is only silence, though perhaps that rustling is,in part, the sound of great wings.  Down below the normal sounds of forestassert themselves, reassuringly familiar.

You stand speechless and awestruck before the enormous Keep.  It is builtof some kind of metal that shines a distinctly reddish hue, similar in colorto blood, which seems to be impenetrable.  The keep boasts no windows, onlyone giant door which allows entrance to this juggernaut of a fortress.

Walls made of a shiny, exotic wood gleam as far as you can see down thehallway of the Keep.  A similar type of wood, not as shiny, lines the floorbut is somewhat covered by surprisingly smooth pieces of some kind of animalfur tied together along the whole length of the gigantic hallway.  Several'trophies' of stuffed animals that are unfamiliar to the land standimposingly in the hallway.  Solid, wooden doors are to you your east andwest, and the magnificent hallway fills the path ahead of you.

Although it did not seem possible by the framework of the Keep'sarchitecture, this room appears to be almost as large as the magnificenthallway from which you just stepped out of.  It almost seems to becomfortable until you notice what is used for, storage of weapons.  Weaponsof all kind are stored here, almost enough to equip huge armies.  Swords,pikes, bows and arrows litter the room.  The worst part is that theyobviously have never been cleaned and the blood of many victims linger aboutthe room.  The feeling of death fills the room.

As you get deeper into the stronghold, the scent and the deathly airabout you only grow stronger.  You now notice horrible torture devices thatsend shivers down the spine of all.  The weapons also seem to have an evilglow about them...  As if they too co ntained the dark hearts that were heldby the ruthless killers.  Many of the weapons are stained so much you wonderif someone bathed them in a pool of blood.  With nearly no light in theroom, it seems suitable to contain only one thing, evil.

The scent and the deathly feeling seem to relent a little, perhapsbecause of the light of hope that you feel when you notice a humble, woodendoor to the west which seems to a door of gold compared to the horridobjects and the personality, as you may call it, of the stronghold which,littered with deadly swords, poisonous arrows, and torture devices that havelong been banished because of the admittance of all of how inhumane theytruly are, seemed to represent death itself, which is feared by all who lovelife.

Downtrodden and dreary, this guard room is unlike any other.  The wallsare blank, only covered by filth and cobwebs.  The cupboard is covered withdust and the only edible thing appears to be a little bug that must eat woodto keep its self alive.  The dull atmosphere contains no sign of life, notlife as in life and death, but any kind of signs that show that thesecreatures actually enjoy life and take pleasure in it.  No gambling game isset up on the table nor no poster of a beautiful member of their species.It seems their existence is to only to work, and apparently the only workthey do is kill.

Nothing remains of the tower except some barely standing walls along thedebris and rubble.  To the east the tumult of battle can be heard, and thescreams, drums and clang of steel against steel cuts through the smoke leftby the fallen tower.

Your eyes squint after catching the gleam of hundreds of different setsof a strange metallic armor.  The sets are much larger then ones of humans,as if they were made for giants.  Huge, black shields the size of almost twohumans line the walls imposing the path of the room.  The shields seem to besomewhat magical, as an eerie light glows around them.  Right above theshields is a shelf lined with monstrous helmets, each capped with a scalpfrom some unfortunate animal.  Some of the scalps are so fresh, that you seefresh, warm blood rolling down the side of the helmet.

Huge breastplates, as long as two hobbits, are stacked and line shelfupon shelf.  The bottom rows contain the newer ones made of the same metalas the eerie glowing shields in the room before.  The upper rows, however,are made of an older metal, more vulnverable, as is shown by the manypunctures and scrapes on the outer shell.  Even though the metal is morevulnerable then the other, it is still a highly respectable armor that canhold it's own in battle which shows that the warriors must have fought insome vicious battles.

The eerie glow from the black leggings that lean against the walls almostmakes you stumble as you enter the room.  For some reason, this end of theHold does not receive much light, so the eerie glow from the evil blackmetal dominates the room's light.  On a shelf above the leggings, are mailshirts and skirts forged of red metal that gives off a similar glow as theblack metal.  You notice a small, crickety old door filled with cobwebs tothe east.

Rooms.EnterMsg: $n makes a little choking sound as $e enters this dreadful little room.
Rooms.ExitMsg: $n gasps and dashes out the door for some clean air!
Rooms.RoomDescription: The smell of decaying flesh and the copper-iron tang of blood permeatesthis room, making you gag.  While the kitchen was filthy, this room is evenworse.  A large chopping block, covered in encrusted blood and hunks offlesh that caught in the wood, stands in the center of the room.  Aslaughtered carcass of some unidentifiable creature lies partiallydismebered on top of it.

A strong, sickly smell hits you as soon as you enter the room.  You beginto wonder what could smell so bad until you notice what this room is usedfor, alchemy.  Long, slim viles line a table filled with dangerous, reddishlooking substance that is giving off a huge cloud of red gas that hangs inthe air right above the vile.  Different containers marked with differentsigns fill glass shelves and from the nature of the shapes, you can tellthat they would be substance that you would drink nor smell.

Fresh air blowing from the window to the east greets you freshly as youwalk into the room.  A couple of old, really old cannons that shot woodencannonballs lean against the wall and despite their prehistoric appearance,it looks like they could still take out an ogre or two.  A short woodenstaircase winds up to the next level of the which is almost visible fromhere.  A picture place right on next to the staircase entrance lies directlyin your vision and the vibrance and life-like appearance of it draws yourattention.

A choking dust hangs heavily in the air as you make your way up thestairs.  You can see large cracks in the walls, gaping sores that may havebeen caused by some kind of projectile.  Through one of the larger cracks,you can glimpse the lush and exotic trees that line the outside of thiskeep.  More dust lies on the stairs, making the surface very slippery.After you almost slip on one step, you resolve to pay more attention to thestairs and less to the scenery outside.  A refreshing draft of cool, freshair beckons you from the top of this tower.

`hA refreshing breeze soothes you as you climb to the top of the tower.From here you can see the whole town and all the houses.  Krathen move allabout, some walking, some flying.  They don't seem to be as imposing fromhere as they are in person when they stand broadly and strongly.  You noticea huge Krathen chair that you guess a guard would sit in as he keeps watch.Apparently the guard must've just had lunch as you see a recently skinnedanimal carcass lying next to the chair.  ``

The hallway, despite having been designed entirely with varying types ofwood, though no marble, gold, or silver, nevertheless holds you in awe.  Thecarefully cut pieces of wood each have intricate designs in them seeminglyshowing an important event in the Krathen history.  Hung on the wall areseveral life-like portraits of what appear to be generals or high militaryofficers.  Their grim appearances show that they were hard men and the lookin their eye shows that they never had mercy for anything.  Intricatelycarved doors are to the east and west, while the hallway continues ahead ofyou.

As you enter the room an extremely noxious smell enters your nostrils asyou enter the mess hall for the Krathen that occupy the Keep.  You noticesome longly stretched wooden tables line the room each filled with varioustypes of food stains that appear to have not been cleaned for years.  Aboutthe room various heads and horns of different animals are hung almost as ifto settle the Krathen hunger as they await their food to be served.  Atleast the floor appears to be clean, since you almost slip on the newlymopped floor as you notice an entrance to some kind of kitchen tot he west.

As you walk in with your head somewhat glancing down, you notice howsoiled the floor is, and it would be considered really dirty for any room,let alone a kitchen.  You also almost jump back as a stanky smell hits yournervous system.  As usual, some luckless orcs have been enslaved to cook forthe enormous Krathen.  Various pots are have steam coming up about of themand you dare not look at their contents, for fear of losing thy stomach.After thoroughly scanning and smelling this kitchen, you quickly lose yourappetite.

Compared to this room, the kitchen looks like a huge, elegant ballroomfit for kings and emperors.  This room is very small, small enough just tofit the four orcs laying lengthwise.  The room is covered in soot, dust anddirt are everywhere.  The sheets on the bed look to have never been changedfor however long the orcs have lived here, which by your estimation of thedirtiness of the room, could be many, many years.  Other then the four bedsthe room is rather barren.  Next to one of the beds you notice a painting ofan orcish family which looks to have been held many a time, which leads youto remember that although orcs can be dirty and insensitive, they still havefeelings.

The maps that once were covering all the walls and tables of thisplanning room are torn down and burned like every other written document theContinuum order can get their zealous hands on.  Anything written that isnot the holy book of Continuum must be incinerated, so it is said by theContinuum Patriarch.

The illustrious, clean kept hallway still sparkles unlike some of theother rooms in the Keep.  You see no signs of dirt or even the smallest hintof a particle of dust.  Why the hallway is kept so clean baffles you,because most of the other rooms are like swamps in a room.  The long animalrug that started at the beginning of the keep comes to an end here, and isreplaced by an exotic elven rug that looks to have been stolen from an elvenpalace because of the royal elven markings on the rug that brightens theroom as the stars do to lands.  To your west is a great opening in which yousee a large room filled with Krathen running to and fro with their weaponsand pointing them about.  To the east is another solid wooden door.

Unlike almost all of the other Krathen rooms, you feel an amusement likeatmosphere to it as you enter.  Quickly, your guess was right as you noticeit is some kind of game room for the Krathen guards to actually relax andhave some fun besides preparing for an attack against the world.  You seeseveral game boards set up of a strange variety that you have never seenbefore, but each one seems to be similar to a particular elven or dwarvishadult game, but it has it's variances.  A long, shiny wooden floor is to theright where you guess the Krathen might actually dance, although it does notseem to fit their violent and malicious nature.  The game room continues,expanding to the east.

This half of the game room, seems to contain some of the more physicalgames.  Long swords line the room that have had their tips cut off so thatthe Krathen can use them without killing each other, as most of themprobably like to do judging from the violence and hurt they love to inflict.Also various kinds of no-tipped spears and old, old shields fill out theroom.  The Krathen must make use of these safe objects to practice theirskills and to have various different competitions.

A huge room filled with various different obstacle courses and what notsurrounds you.  You see Krathen trainees running about swords in handyelling Krathen war shouts as they prepare for their time as a guard andwarrior.  Some of the courses seem very entertaining and even interest youin maybe taking a shot in taking a run through one of them.  The wholegymnasium is well orgainized and the training session is very wellorganized.  Different lines line the room and different paths around theobstacles.  The gymnasium continues to the north and west.

This particular area of the gymnasium seems to concentrate on the usageof various types of weapons.  Various human, elven, and dwarven targets areset up about the area and the trainees run about bobbing and weavingshooting arrows or throwing spears at the targets.  As you are watchingthis, a trainee hits a target square in the crotch, which forces you togrimace and hope that they are not as accurate in a real battle.  Thegymnasium expands northwards and eastwards.

In this section of the gymnasium the Krathen practice their combatmovements and advances.  You are curious about this section because of theiroverwhelming excellent agility which is strange due to their great size andthe presence of their wings.  You notice this course is very strenous.Different tubes with various widths and lengths lay about the room linkingvarious land pads and nets from which the Krathen climb about or run upon.The entrance to the gymnasium is to the south and the defense section is tothe west.

This part of the gymnasium teaches the trainees various kinds of defensetactics.  Like the weapons gymnasium, various type of targets are set upabout the room, but they are different in that they are made to throw orswing their different weapons as the Krathen makes his way around them andto the finish line of the course.  You are startled as one trainee is slainby a target as they use real swords for training.  You look to the mob oftrainees for some kind of reaction to the death, but they carry off the deadKrathen, grunt, and quickly continue to train.

The wood of the Hallway shines and gleams as ye stroll along it.  Again,pictures of victorous Krathen line the wall elegantly placed in old, butworthy looking frames.  The wood feels nice and soft, at ye feet, almost asif it were some kind of a carpet and it tempts you to want to lay down uponit.  Although, it is very soft, a quick stomp of your foot shows it is alsovery sturdy and reliable.  After your little test, you glance up ahead andlook at what looks to be an intersection ahead in the hallway, where itdivides and heads off in the directions of east and west.

Finally, the great hallway changes directions.  Still neatly kept, thepath to the north ends, and is replace by a way to the east.  To the eastthe hallway seems to be a bit smaller and not as decorated as the hallway isnow.  To the east is a small, but finely made, wooden door, that appears tolead to some kind of a guest room.  Above the door is another strangeKrathen marking that ye can not make out which may prove to make yourguestimate invalid.

As you stand on the circular stairwell, you notice how carefully andaccurately the stairs were constructed, and earns your respect as aremarkably made structure.  The stairs, unlike almost the rest of the wholeKeep, including the village, are made of a metallic substance that feels andlooks like no other metal ye have ever seen.  It is of a woodish color, butit is not wood, although the thought crosses your mind because of theannoying clicking sound it makes as you clod up the stairs.  It gives alight, light glow that almost energizes you and gives you the feel you arewalking on air.  The rail is made of the same type of metal, and your nervestingle with excitement as you use your hands to guide your way up thestairs, noticing how extremely smooth the rail seems to be.  Upwards, yousee what looks to be the roof of the Keep, where the wind seems to beblowing violently.

Now that hallway has changed course, it is much smaller and not aselitely decorated and exotic as it was at the beginning of the Hallway.  Itis now much plainer and conservative.  The sweet, soft wood that was usedearlier is now replaced with harsh, poorly treated wood that will give manya bare-footed children plenty of splinters.  The walls lay about almostnonexistent with no decoration or pictures.  The room appears to be as bareas an old hags cabinet.  You just realize as you glance up that the hallwayends here, and only two wooden doors, to your north and south, and the wayback west are the only exits.

Although the Krathen appear to be a rather dull and boring race, thequarters of the guard appears to be very lively and well decorated, verysurprising from your past experiences with them.  Different objects, sometrivial, some valuable, fill sturdy wooden desks that stand against thewall.  Some objects resemble old Krathen, while others appear to be oldheroes of the Elven, Human, and Dwarven races, which surprises ye because ofhow much they believe that they are the superior race and should dominate,but the figures seem to show that they do have a certain respect for otherraces.  Surprisingly short beds, well short for a normal Krathen line theroom and you wonder how they sleep in these scruffy old beds and still findmotivation to get up in the morning.  The wall are filled with variouspictures and drawings varying from the local, beautiful landscape to thefavorite Krathen pin-up girl.

The room almost appears to have a glowing aura about it as you enter,large statues, 3 to be exact, separate 4 different beds.  The statues are ofthe Krathen race and show the Krathen armed with dangerous weapons, drenchedwith blood dripping here and there, and slight, childish smirk that sendsshivers down your spine as you look at it.  The beds are remarkably shortconsidering they hold the mighty Krathen, who could easily fill up two ofthose beds if you were to line them up and connect them.  Directly acrossfrom the bed and the statues is one giant desk that sits four differentseats and each seat has it's own workspot.  Some of the workspots areblandly decorated, with the usual Krathen medal hung about, one of thestands out though, it has colorful drawings and humorous figurines placedaround it, almost as if this Krathen had a sense of humor, definetly worthyof meeting with.

Rooms.RoomName: Upon the roof of the Keep
Rooms.RoomDescription: Here on the top of the roof, you only see the tops of the large trees formiles and miles, almost appearing to never end.  You are almost taken abackwhen you feel and see the wind wreaking havoc up here.  Trees are beingtossed about with no effort and you feared for your life several times whena tree almost bent over and knocked you on the head.  As you are avoidingthe trees, you struggle to stand up straight as the wind takes it's turn onyou.  You have never seen winds this violent and vicious, and decide it mustnot be normal, as you turn to the south, you see an area to where the windlooks to be almost a hundred fold worse, and bright light coming from thearea, that seems to draw you there.

Here is the throne of the mighty Krathe, the betrayer of humans, andenemy to all races save the Krathen.  As your eyes adjust to the sumptiousroom before you, it becomes immediately obvious that Krathe enjoys hispleasures, and spare no expense in pursuing them.  As you stand in thislavish outdoor throne room, you realize that some kind of magic must,whenever rain or snow fall, protect this room and maintain a constanttemperature pleasing to the tyrant Krathe around the general area of histhrone.  His throne is a majestic sight indeed, covered with gold andnumerous diamonds, even the legendary diamond of the Krathen, and looms overthe other furnishings in the room, as an eagle in an eyrie might survey itsdomain.  As Krathe is much bigger then the ordinary human, the throne isalso large, as it might be able to fit a Krathen.  It would be better if itwere a Krathen that sat upon the throne, rather than the foul scum Krathe,the starter of wars and bringer of death.

Rooms.MaxMsg: The dungeon is too cramped to allow you to enter.
Rooms.EnterMsg: $n comes tumbling in from the trapdoor above.
Rooms.ExitMsg: $n climbs out into the light of the alchemy lab.
Rooms.RoomDescription: This damp dreary hole seems to be where the alchemist keeps his specimenswhen he isn't working on them in the laboratory up above.  The air isunwholesome and chills you with the lingering presence of death.  All aboutyou are strewn odd bits of limbs and bones.  It might be wise to leavebefore the Alchemist comes to experiment upon you.
